The expression $|z^2 + z - 2|$ can be rewritten as $|z^2 + z - 2| = |(z - 1)(z + 2)| = |z - 1||z + 2|$. Since $|z| = 1$, we can let $z = e^{i\theta}$. Then $|z - 1| = |e^{i\theta} - 1| = \sqrt{2 - 2\cos\theta}$ and $|z + 2| = |e^{i\theta} + 2| = \sqrt{5 + 4\cos\theta}$. The minimum value of $|z^2 + z - 2|$ occurs when $\cos\theta = -1$, which gives $|z - 1| = 2$ and $|z + 2| = 1$. Therefore, the minimum value of $|z^2 + z - 2|$ is $2 \cdot 1 = 2$. \boxed{2}

